          "body": "The book of Ruth never reports the LORD speaking directly, never narrates a miracle, never describes a vision. But the narrator opens his theological framing at 1:6 — 'the LORD had visited His people in giving them food' — using the verb *paqad*, the covenant-intervention verb of Genesis 21:1 (the LORD visited Sarah) and Exodus 4:31 (the LORD visited His people in Egypt). This single verbal note tells the reader that everything that follows is the LORD's quiet doing, even when the characters cannot see it. The chapter closes with a deceptively simple temporal note: 'they came to Bethlehem at the beginning of barley harvest' (1:22). Barley harvest is late April / early May, the season of Firstfruits (Leviticus 23:10). The 'empty' woman has been brought home precisely at the moment when food is again pouring out of the house of bread. The reader who knows what is coming in chapter 2 — the gleaning field, Boaz, the kinsman-redeemer — sees that the LORD's hand has been on Naomi the whole time. The chapter's last line is the narrator's first answer to her despair: emptiness was the doorway to harvest."
